result.execSummary:
The defendant Trevor Q Neitzel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: Repeater], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

If probation or extended supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Jury trial - 12 person on March 11, 2015 at 08:30 am.
for Preliminary Hearing held October 14, 2014.  (Michelle L. Peterson, Court Reporter)

Defendant Trevor Q Neitzel in court with attorney Travis Stephen Slattery.  Defendant Trevor Q Neitzel in custody.  Craig Lambert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Not guilty pleas entered.  Bond continued.

2:46 Defendant Trevor Q Neitzel in court with attorney Travis Stephen Slattery.  Defendant Trevor Q Neitzel in custody.  Craig Lambert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Kevin Hamill is sworn as a witness.  Testifies to his employment with Marshfield Police Dept.  Testifies to investigation of robberies at Subway and Taco John's on or about 03/13/14.  There was no consent to enter either restaurant.  Testifies to the location of both restaurants.  Testifies to interview with Brandon Jacobson and that Jacobson indicated that he dropped off Neitzel and Korpal at businesses.  Knows Trevor Neitzel and identifies him in the courtroom.  

Atty Slattery cross examines the witness.  Testifies to what Jacobson indicated he saw and why he felt they were going to break into the businesses.  Testifies to other evidence found at businesses.  

Atty Lambert moves for bind over.  Atty Slattery presents argument.  

Court finds probable cause and proceeds to Arraignment.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for November 21, 2014 at 10:00 am.
Preliminary hearing and Arraignment on October 14, 2014 at 02:15 pm.
